HEADER: Gorman & Yang (2017) - When nobody wins
TITLE: When nobody wins
AUTHORTITLE: Gorman & Yang (2017)
RAWAUTHORS: <a href="/lingbuzz/003614?_s=nzvTMn7n0vKACwAh&amp;_k=O2tjMT6-G6pfB_QR&amp;1">Kyle Gorman</a>, <a href="/lingbuzz/003614?_s=nzvTMn7n0vKACwAh&amp;_k=O2tjMT6-G6pfB_QR&amp;2">Charles Yang</a>
AUTHORS: Kyle Gorman, Charles Yang
LASTNAMES: Gorman, Yang
MONTH: June
YEAR: 2017
ABSTRACT: As young children vividly illustrate with their performance on the wug-test (Berko 1958), the ability to generalize linguistic patterns to novel items is a core property of language. It thus comes as a surprise when we stumble into a dark and dusty corner of language where our boundless linguistic productivity has unexpectedly failed. We propose that such lexical gaps arise in precisely those linguistic contexts for which the Tolerance Principle (Yang 2005, 2016) identifies no productive generalizations. We illustrate this proposal with detailed case studies from Spanish, Polish, and Russian.
